description:
Fish Head Nebula is located in a star-forming region in the northern constellation Cassiopeia and is about 6,000 light-years away. This colorful cosmic glowing gas and obscuring dust clouds look like the head of a fish. 
This is a Hubble Palette (SHO) narrowband imaging that NASA tends to use RGB mapping with Sulphur II, Ha, OIII filter data. The stars are recorded through broadband filters.


Technical details:
Telescope: TEC 160FL + TEC FRC 0.9x
Mount: Astro-Physics Mach 2 GTO
Imaging cameras:ZWO ASI6200MM 
Software: PHD2, PixInsight, Lightroom 6.4, Sequence Generator Pro, Photoshop CS6
Location: Palo Alto, California, USA

Resolution ............... 0.783 arcsec/px
Rotation ................. -89.906 deg
Observation start time ... 2020-11-09 03:55:28 UTC
Observation end time ..... 2020-11-27 11:00:38 UTC
Focal distance ........... 989.88 mm
Pixel size ............... 3.76 um
Field of view ............ 2d 5' 2.6" x 1d 23' 24.9" (before corp)
Image center ............. RA:  2 27 02.160  Dec: +61 51 13.98


Filters: Astrodon 50mm Unmounted LRGB Gen2 E-Series Filter Sets
         Astrodon 50mm Unmounted 3nm Narrowband Ha, SII, OIII filters
Blue  74x60"  1 hour 14 Minutes   Bin2x2     11/19/2020
Green 74x60"  1 Hour 14 Minutes Bin2x2       11/19/2020
Red   74x60"  1 Hour 14 Minutes Bin2x2       11/19/2020
